;Minutes: [[IRC Meeting/Minutes]]

=== Pre-meeting ===
# Organiser creates agenda for next meeting and posts it to [[IRC Meeting/Agenda]].
# Organiser announces next meeting on [http://lists.xmms.se/cgi-bin/mailman/listinfo/xmms2-devel mailing list], most preferably 4 days before the meeting, at the latest. Announcement includes proposed agenda.
# Participants prepare a list of issues they want to address. If there are any major issues to talk about, that haven't been addressed by the proposed agenda, participants negotiate with organiser to include them. Even if the organiser cannot fit a certain issue into the agenda (e.g. due to time constraints), it may be brought up after the meeting. That is, agenda items are to be given priority.
#* Alternatively, participants may edit the latest agenda on the [[IRC Meeting/Agenda | wiki]], but it's up to the organiser to take those modifications into account when starting the next meeting.

=== Meeting ===
# Participants join channel and wait for organiser to announce the start of the meeting.
# Organiser asks each participant to announce their [[#Status_announcements | status]].
# <code>for issue in issues: Organiser picks issue to discuss - participants discuss.</code>
# Organiser may defer discussion of certain issues to a later date (e.g. next meeting) or to the mailing list if the discussion is taking too long, and there are other issues to address on the agenda.

=== Wrapup ===
# Participants may assign action items (things to do), and report on the progress of these items at the next meeting.
# Organiser summarises meeting (possibly with meeting minutes) - such a summary can be useful for planning subsequent meetings (e.g. new agenda items).

=== Post-meeting ===
*coffee
*donuts
*code

== Meeting channel rules and guidelines ==
* The channel is muted (+m) - participants will be automatically voiced (+v) when joining the channel, but may be devoiced (-v) if they are disruptive.

== Status announcements ==
At the start of each meeting, participants should indicate their current status (wrt project issues) using the following keywords:
;DONE: What he has done since last meeting
;TODO: Items on his todo list
;BLOCKED: Items he can't progress on, due to various factors (to be discussed)
;DISCUSS: Item to be discussed during meeting

When asked by the organiser, the participant should ideally paste these prepared lines into the channel. For example:

 <FooMaster> joe: what's your status?
 <joe> DONE: Implemented libkorv and fixed BeOS port
 <joe> TODO: Add more documentation
 <joe> BLOCKED: Get new git repo for libkorv
 <joe> DISCUSS: Whether to depend on bierlib or pilsnerlib

